			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ylaines post prompted me to run some tests on just what effect AC has on our pets when tanking. From doing these tests the conclusion I've come to is that:
<br />

<br />
Our pets are summoned as NAKED Lvl 60 Warriors. This means they have a natural AC of around 680.
<br />

<br />
As I've already taken data with pets unarmoured and equipped with mostly summoned gear against Blood Ravens in PoN, as I don't have access to a boxed cleric I rely on just my heals to keep the pet standing so need fairly weak mobs to test on.
<br />

<br />
I visited the Bazaar and spent a few k on gear to equip pet with so I could test it at AC values far higher than what can be achieved just using summoned gear. I used added raw AC values of 0, 105, 203 and 303 for these tests and the results were:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
AC&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Mean&nbsp; &nbsp;DPS&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Acc&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;%Max&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;%Min&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;MC
<br />
0&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 180&nbsp; &nbsp; 60.8&nbsp; &nbsp; 61.7&nbsp; &nbsp; 26.3&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 9.1&nbsp; &nbsp; 0.600&nbsp; &nbsp;
<br />
105&nbsp; &nbsp; 160&nbsp; &nbsp; 55.7&nbsp; &nbsp; 60.8&nbsp; &nbsp; 16.4&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;17.8&nbsp; &nbsp; 0.507
<br />
203&nbsp; &nbsp; 138&nbsp; &nbsp; 48.0&nbsp; &nbsp; 58.9&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;9.0&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;22.8&nbsp; &nbsp; 0.405
<br />
303&nbsp; &nbsp; 125&nbsp; &nbsp; 43.7&nbsp; &nbsp; 59.1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6.5&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;30.7&nbsp; &nbsp; 0.344
<br />

<br />
Mean = Mean hit &#40;discounting bash/kick&#41; pet took
<br />
DPS = Total DPS pet took whilst tanking
<br />
Acc = Mob percentage accuracy
<br />
%Max = Percentage of the hits that landed for maximum
<br />
%Min = Percentage of the hits that landed for minimum
<br />
MC = Sleethr's Mitigation Coefficent defined as &#40;Mean - Min&#41; / &#40;Max - Min&#41;
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It can be seen that adding better armour makes a huge difference in the pets ability to tank. 
<br />

<br />
How does the added AC on the pet compared to if that armour was placed on a PC tank?. The 303 raw ac would be displayed as 485 ac, added to the 680 base and the 22 from Burnout 5 would give this hypothetical Lvl 60 warrior an AC of 1185. No idea how how 1200 unbuffed AC compares to real lvl 60 tanks but it doesn't seem that unreasonable.
<br />

<br />
If you added more AC to the pets then you will see further gains just as you would for a player tank. You do get diminishing returns though as you add more AC as you cannot mitigate a hit below minimum so you get a 'pile' up at minimum hits as can be seen from the table above.
<br />

<br />
I think the main problem with our pets is that we simply cannot add enough AC through summoned gear to make a significant difference to how they tank due to them been summoned effectively naked.
<br />

<br />
So how much more AC would we need to give to the pet to get it to tank reasonably well?
<br />

<br />
I've found that for a specific value of AC the Mitigation Coefficient is pretty stable (based on the data from Blood Ravens, Nettling Wraiths, Planarian larvae, tactics pit mob and Guardian of Marr) which indicates that PoP mobs simply scale in the DPS they dish out in a predicatable manner.
<br />

<br />
Using the values obtained with summoned armour (the 105ac line, though for some tests I used 129 ac so that will introduce some error here) we can predict what the appromixate mob DPS would have been if the pet had 300 added AC (a approximately 21% reduction in dps taken going from 105 to 300ac) and if the pet had 400'ish added AC (estimated as been a 29% reduction from the 105ac line, based on a Blood Raven doing 40dps at 400'ish ac) 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
Mob&nbsp; &nbsp; 105ac&nbsp; &nbsp; 303ac&nbsp; &nbsp;400ac
<br />
BR&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;55.7&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;44.0&nbsp; &nbsp; 40.0&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 
<br />
NW&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;75.0&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;59.3&nbsp; &nbsp; 53.3
<br />
PL&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;99.0&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;78.2&nbsp; &nbsp; 70.3
<br />
Tac&nbsp; &nbsp; 122&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 96.4&nbsp; &nbsp; 86.6
<br />
GoM&nbsp; &nbsp; 133&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;105.1&nbsp; &nbsp; 94.4
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Having tried to pet tank these mobs solo I think the 400'ish ac dps figures would probably let us solo semi-efficiently in Tier 2. 
<br />

<br />
To achieve this what I think would be the best solution is to add AC to the 2 summoned belts we currently have.
<br />

<br />
Adding 150 AC to the Belt of Magikot and 300 AC to the Girdle (thereby letting you add another 130 ac from the full summoned suit/focus items) would probably make our pets acceptable tanks without stepping on PC tanks toes given high AC gear is so much easier to obtain nowadays than a year ago.
<br />

<br />
The exact figures of course would be to be tested in a real environment and not just guesstimated like I have done here. Of course these are based on PoP mobs aswell and I'd expect GoD mobs to be tougher still and do more dps at a specific level but the avoidance/ND AA should help with that. This also doesn't address the concerns that the various pet foci should affect mitigation aswell.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
