			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Do pets parry/dodge/riposte very well, if at all?  Those skills really have an impact as well.  I've read a thread on the cleric's boards that basically defensive-related skills is what the difference is between a cleric "tanking" and a paladin tanking, assuming equal shown AC.  They mitigate the same, but dodge/riposte/parry on the paladin makes the difference in being hit.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Kailyn wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Ummm I think you better check your stop watch, there is no way a normal LDoN mob is putting out 300 DPS+ to kill your pet in 10 seconds.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
300+ dps isn't too impossible in LDoN normal for an unslowed mob tripling 300-400.  I've tanked there as a 60 ranger.  I wish there had been a cleric.  All I had was a shaman and a druid to keep me alive (They didn't twice).  But it was fun though.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Arhallia wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">As a side-issue, Kunark-era warriors didn't have 6k hp unbuffed, either. 5k in an uber guild... maybe. Closer to 4500 unbuffed would be my guess, actually. Remember AAs didn't even exist until Luclin, and much of the readily available "good" Kunark gear didn't even have good stats. The VP loot wasn't exactly high in the hp dept, either. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wow, you're thinking it was that high?  I thought it was more 3500-4k, getting to be 5.5-6k in Velious.  Unbuffed.  There's very, very few 100 hp items in Kunark's end-game.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>EmiliaEQ wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Lets eliminate AA & FT because these do not represent player power. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That is not true.  AA is CRITICAL to player power.  The 36 Luclin defensive AAs and 30 PoP defensive AAs are a HUGE change in tanking to any class.  Not going into offensive AAs, as those change per class.
<br />

<br />
I do love your ideas about linking pet Hp/AC to the pet though.
<br />

<br />
I no longer countenance that mage pets should always be able to tank something however.  A mage pet, as is, is basically an unbuffed, AA-less warrior on a CR, with sub-Kunark armor, and a pair of swords.  And with a master that heals less per second at 64 than a 55 druid spamming Chloroblast.  You don't send a naked unbuffed warrior without a healer against an exp mob past...level 45 or so?
<br />

<br />
On the flip side, a 5 non-melee group+mage is GOING to have buffers in the group, and at least one healer and slower class (3 casters and 3 priest classes, there should be a shaman/enchanter or cleric/druid.  Someone to heal and someone to slow)
<br />

<br />
So, in such a group where the pet tanks, it's going to have much better buffs.  P9, Stamina, Kazad's, and Focus is something like 2500 extra hp to me.  Probably be more on the pet, coded as a warrior.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Our pets are summoned as NAKED Lvl 60 Warriors. This means they have a natural AC of around 680.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Woot!  Just what I always suspected, being coded as warrior mobs=being a naked PC warrior.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Warriors still have the best damage mitigation. Pets should be better than priests as priests can immediately self heal (unless the pet somehow knows how to self-heal when they get hit -- the delay in the UI and casting time of Mage pet heals is not a substitute for sub-four-second self heals.)</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'm not familiar with any "self heals" priests get.  And yes, I (62 ranger) beat out any mage spamming heals on a pet, in terms of hp per second due to long cast times and a recast time on mage heals, and chloroblast being 428 with a 3 second base, with the usual 2.25 second recast.
<br />

<br />
And I get AA to improve heal size and can crit heal (when I get the AA to).
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">summary</span>
<br />
1.  Pets ARE equivalent to warriors, if they had equivalent gear, buffs, and weapons.  They have about 1/10th the raw AC availiable from summoned items, and aren't buffed unless they HAVE to be.
<br />

<br />
I favor Reston's idea.  It scales the best.  The main down side is that mages AC is basically capped far below anyone else's.  "What, you want a 60 AC hat so your PET gets more AC?!" <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
2.  Even the most god-awefully super-uber "I wear 5 inch thick plates of planar steel on my chest" tanks need heals to back him up, and a ranger, a RANGER out heals a level 64 mage starting at level 62.  (Yes, you have mend companion, I have AA to heal 19% more and crit heal chances).  And cast speed focii help me more than help mages' heals.
<br />

<br />
Mage heals need rebalancing without stepping on beastlords' toes.  Beastlord's slow already helps significantly with healing.<br />_________________<br />Darlatan Firemist
<br />
62 ranger
